value.value: A homeostatic process involved in the maintenance of a steady state level of arginine within a cell.
The process in which the basal boundary between the stem and both vegetative and reproductive organs are established and maintained.
Catalysis of the reaction: 9,9',15-tri-cis-zeta-carotene = 9,9'-di-cis-zeta-carotene.
Any protein processing achieved by the cleavage of a peptide bond after two basic amino acids within a protein.
Any protein processing achieved by the cleavage of a peptide bond after a lysine-arginine amino acid residue combination within a protein.
Any protein processing achieved by the cleavage of a peptide bond after two consecutive arginine amino acid residues within a protein.
Any protein processing achieved by the cleavage of a peptide bond after two consecutive lysine amino acid residues within a protein.

The process in which a purine nucleotide-sugar is transported across a membrane. Purine nucleotide-sugars are purine nucleotides in glycosidic linkage with a monosaccharide or monosaccharide derivative.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

value.value: The process in which a pyrimidine nucleotide-sugar is transported across a membrane. Pyrimidine nucleotide-sugars are pyrimidine nucleotides in glycosidic linkage with a monosaccharide or monosaccharide derivative.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

value.value: Enables the transfer of a vitamin from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the reaction: phosphatidylglycerol + phosphatidylethanolamine = cardiolipin + ethanolamine.

Catalysis of the transfer of a methyl group from S-adenosyl-L-methionine to the oxygen atom of a nucleoside residue in a small RNA molecule. Reaction: S-adenosyl-L-methionine + small RNA = S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + small RNA containing a 3'-terminal 2'-O-methylnucleotide.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of secondary metabolites, the compounds that are not necessarily required for growth and maintenance of cells, and are often unique to a taxon.
Binding to a polo box domain of a protein. The polo box domain is involved in binding substrates of polo kinases.

Catalyzes the multi-step reaction: L-tryptophan + 2 O2 + 2 reduced [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase] = (E)-(indol-3-yl)acetaldehyde oxime + CO2 + 2 H+ + 3 H2O + 2 oxidized [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase].
The directed movement of catecholamine into a cell.
The directed movement of dopamine into a cell.
The disaggregation of a low-density lipoprotein particle into its constituent components.

label.value: mesenchyme migration involved in limb bud formation

value.value: The migration of mesenchymal tissue that contributes to the formation of a limb bud.
The orderly movement of a mesenchymal cell from one site to another, often during the development of a multicellular organism.
The component of a Golgi membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

label.value: pimelyl-[acyl-carrier protein] methyl ester esterase activity

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: 6-carboxyhexanoyl-[ACP] methyl ester + H2O = 6-carboxyhexanoyl-[ACP] + H+ + methanol.

definition.value: Note that while this reaction occurs on a modified protein (acyl-carrier protein), the ACP only acts as a carrier that later releases the end product.

value.value: A transition where an endocardial cushion cell loses apical/basolateral polarity, severs intercellular adhesive junctions, degrades basement membrane components and becomes a migratory mesenchymal cell.
The expansion of one cell sheet over other cells or yolk.
The expansion of one cell sheet over other cells involved in wound healing.
A developmental process that results in the initiation of an axillary shoot meristem. An axillary shoot meristem is a shoot meristem formed in the axil of a leaf.

label.value: phenylethylamine metabolic process involved in synaptic transmission

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways involving phenylethylamine that contribute to synaptic transmission.

label.value: phenylethylamine biosynthetic process involved in synaptic transmission

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of phenylethylamine that contribute to synaptic transmission.
A cell division process where the division plane is perpendicular to the surface of the organ. It adds cells to the existing cell layer or cell file.
A cell division process where the division plane is parallel to the surface of the organ. It creates a new cell layer or cell file.
A plasma membrane part that is composed of a furrow-like plasma membrane domain and associated integral transmembrane proteins.
The directed movement of L-histidine into the vacuole across the vacuolar membrane.
The directed movement of L-tyrosine into the vacuole across the vacuolar membrane.
The directed movement of L-glutamate into the vacuole across the vacuolar membrane.
The directed movement of L-serine into the vacuole across the vacuolar membrane.
The directed movement of L-lysine into the vacuole across the vacuolar membrane.
The directed movement of L-arginine into the vacuole across the vacuolar membrane.
Any process in which an organism or cell protects itself from anoxia, which may also result in resistance to repeated exposure to anoxia.
The series of molecular signals mediated by a sphingolipid.
The orderly movement of a podocyte from one site to another, often during the development of a multicellular organism or multicellular structure. A podocyte is a specialized kidney epithelial cell.

The initial, indirect interaction between a secretory vesicle membrane and a site of exocytosis in the plasma membrane. This interaction is mediated by tethering factors (or complexes), which interact with both membranes. Interaction can occur via direct binding to membrane phospholipids or membrane proteins, or via binding to vesicle coat proteins. This process is distinct from and prior to docking and fusion.

label.value: cytochrome-b5 reductase activity, acting on NADPH

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: NADPH + H+ + 2 ferricytochrome b(5) = NADP+ + 2 ferrocytochrome b(5).

label.value: cytochrome-b5 reductase activity, acting on NADH

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: NADH + H+ + 2 ferricytochrome b(5) = NAD+ + 2 ferrocytochrome b(5).
The assembly of a smooth septate junction, a septate junction that lacks the regular arrays of electron-dense septae found in pleated septate junctions.

The assembly and arrangement of a cellular component that is composed of peptidoglycan and often chitin in addition to other materials and usually forms perpendicular to the long axis of a cell or hypha. It grows centripetally from the cell wall to the center of the cell and often functions in the compartmentalization of a cell into two daughter cells.

label.value: L-ascorbic acid biosynthetic process via GDP-alpha-D-mannose

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of L-ascorbic acid via the intermediate GDP-alpha-D-mannose.

label.value: L-ascorbic acid biosynthetic process via UDP-alpha-D-glucuronate

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of L-ascorbic acid via the intermediate UDP-alpha-D-glucuronate.

definition.value: This pathway occurs in most vertebrates, although not in guinea pigs and primates, including humans.

value.value: Protein complex that carries out the reaction: ATP + H2O + cation(out) = ADP + phosphate + cation(in).
Protein complex that carries out the reaction: ATP + H2O + Ca2+(out) = ADP + phosphate + Ca2+(in).

An ISWI complex that contains an ATPase subunit of the ISWI family (specifically SNF2H in mammals, which contain two ISWI homologs) and WSTF (Williams Syndrome Transcription Factor). WICH plays roles in regulation of RNAP I and III transcription and in DNA replication and repair.
